A p-value less than 0.05 (typically ≤ 0.05) is statistically significant. … A p-value higher than 0.05 (> 0.05) is not statistically significant and indicates weak evidence against the null hypothesis. This means we fail to reject the null hypothesis and cannot accept the alternative hypothesis

grubbs.test(crime) #Default
## 
##  Grubbs test for one outlier
## 
## data:  crime
## G = 2.81287, U = 0.82426, p-value = 0.07887
## alternative hypothesis: highest value 1993 is an outlier

p-value > 0.05 we fail to reject the null hypothesis, i.e. 1993 is not an outlier, hence we cannot accept the alternative hypothesis

grubbs.test(crime, two.sided = TRUE) #Default
## 
##  Grubbs test for one outlier
## 
## data:  crime
## G = 2.81287, U = 0.82426, p-value = 0.1577
## alternative hypothesis: highest value 1993 is an outlier

p-value > 0.05 we fail to reject the null hypothesis, i.e. 1993 is not an outlier, hence we cannot accept the alternative hypothesis

grubbs.test(crime, opposite = TRUE) #Default
## 
##  Grubbs test for one outlier
## 
## data:  crime
## G = 1.45589, U = 0.95292, p-value = 1
## alternative hypothesis: lowest value 342 is an outlier

p-value > 0.05 we fail to reject the null hypothesis, i.e. 342 is not an outlier, hence we cannot accept the alternative hypothesis

grubbs.test(crime, type=11) # lowest and highest
## 
##  Grubbs test for two opposite outliers
## 
## data:  crime
## G = 4.26877, U = 0.78103, p-value = 1
## alternative hypothesis: 342 and 1993 are outliers

p-value > 0.05 we fail to reject the null hypothesis, i.e. 342 and 1993 are not outliers, hence we cannot accept the alternative hypothesis

grubbs.test(crime, type=11, opposite = TRUE) #
## 
##  Grubbs test for two opposite outliers
## 
## data:  crime
## G = 4.26877, U = 0.78103, p-value = 1
## alternative hypothesis: 342 and 1993 are outliers

p-value > 0.05 we fail to reject the null hypothesis, i.e. 342 and 1993 are not outliers, hence we cannot accept the alternative hypothesis

Since we failed to reject the null hypothesis in all the above grubbs test, we can say that there are no outliers in the Crime data, as per grubbs test

Question 6.1

Describe a situation or problem from your job, everyday life, current events, etc., for which a Change Detection model would be appropriate. Applying the CUSUM technique, how would you choose the critical value and the threshold?

I hike every weekend and the terrain is pretty much the same (different mountains but similar distance and altitude). I’d use CUSUM to detect any change in my rythm/stamina/performance over the last few months. I will be detecting an increase in time taken so CUSUM for detecting an increase will be my approach. On an average if I take 60 mins for a 3 mile hike, I’d expect to be within 5 mins of my average, so my Threshold would be 6 The Critical value in this case will be a number much less than the difference between my data point and the mean (60 min/hike), which is normally 0<=n<=5. So 2 seems to be a good value to start with.

Question 6.2

  1. Using July through October daily-high-temperature data for Atlanta for 1996 through 2015, use

  • CUSUM approach to identify when unofficial summer ends (i.e., when the weather starts cooling off) each year. You can get the data that you need from the file temps.txt or online, for example at http://www.iweathernet.com/atlanta-weather-records or https://www.wunderground.com/history/airport/KFTY/2015/7/1/CustomHistory.html . You can use R if you’d like, but it’s straightforward enough that an Excel spreadsheet can easily do the job too.

  • Use a CUSUM approach to make a judgment of whether Atlanta’s summer climate has gotten warmer in that time (and if so, when).

we are trying to find when unofficial summer ends,i.e. decreasing change, so St=max(0,S{t-1}+(mu-xt-C))

#Calculate Xt-Mu for every year
xt_mu<-apply(weatherdata[,-1],1,'-',weathermeans)

#reverse signs i.e. mu-Xt since we are tracking decrease
mu_xt <- (apply(xt_mu,1,'*',-1))

#Lets set C = 0.5 of SD
C<-Sdmatrix*0.5

# subract C 
mu_xt_c <-apply(mu_xt,1,'-',C)
mu_xt_c<-t(mu_xt_c)

#dimensions of the matrix for declaring St matrix
m<-dim(mu_xt)[1]
n<-dim(mu_xt)[2]
#St matrix declaration
St<-matrix(rep(0),nrow=m,ncol=n)

#Calculate St, cusum
for( j in 1:n){
  St_1<-0
  for(i in 1:m){
    St_1<- max(0,St_1+as.numeric(mu_xt_c[i,j]))
    St[i,j]<-St_1
  }
}

#set column names and also append the "day of the month" information
colnames(St)<-colnames(weatherdata[,-1])
St<-cbind(as.matrix(weatherdata[,1]),St)

colnames(St)[1] <- "Day"

#Lets plot the values of St and try few Threshold values
Threshold<-c(meanSd*5,meanSd*7,meanSd*9,meanSd*11)
colnamThreshold<-c("5","7","9","11")
colorv<-c("red","blue","black","purple")


par(mfcol=c(1,2))

#1996-2000
matplot(y = St[,2:6], type = 'l', lty = 1, col = "black")
for(i in 1:length(Threshold)) {
abline(Threshold[i],0,col=colorv[i])
}
legend(legend = colnamThreshold, x = "topleft", y = "topleft", lty = 1, lwd = 2, col = colorv)



#2000-2005
matplot(y = St[,7:12], type = 'l', lty = 1, col = "black")

abline(Threshold[i],0,col=colorv[i])
}
legend(legend = colnamThreshold, x = "topleft", y = "topleft", lty = 1, lwd = 2, col = colorv)

Based on the graphs above a Threshold of 7*Standard Deviation seems to detect the change effectively

Thold<-(Sdmatrix * 7)

#Find unofficial summer ends for each year
summermat<-matrix(nrow=2,ncol=n)
dim(summermat)
## [1]  2 20
colnames(summermat)<-colnames(weatherdata[,-1])

#recalculate the dimensions
ms<-dim(St)[1]
ns<-dim(St)[2]

#Find the tip-over point i.e. the change in temperature for every year
# go column by column, i.e. year by year
for (j in 2:ns){
  
# go row by row, i.e. day by day  
  for(i in 1:ms){
    dayVal<-as.numeric(St[i,j])
    Th<-Thold[j-1]
    if( dayVal > Th ) {
      
      summermat[1,j-1]<- St[i,1]
      summermat[2,j-1]<- weatherdata[i,j]
      break
    }
      
  }
}

When summer really ends, there are few false detections for example in 1999 and 2007, however overall the model seems to detect the change.

  • Use a CUSUM approach to make a judgment of whether Atlanta’s summer climate has gotten warmer in that time (and if so, when). Here we are detecting an increase summer temperature over the years
#Calculate the mean temperature for summer months across all years
summermean<-mean(weathermeans)
xt_mu<-apply(as.matrix(weathermeans),1,'-',summermean)
#Calculate the standard deviation for summer months across all years
sd<-mean(apply(as.matrix(weathermeans),2,sd))

sd
## [1] 1.86771
Thhold <- sd*1.5
C<-(sd)*0.2

C
## [1] 0.3735419
#calculate Xt-mu-C
xt_mu_c <-as.matrix(apply(as.matrix(xt_mu),1,'-',C))


m<-dim(xt_mu_c)[1]
n<-dim(xt_mu_c)[2]

#St matrix
St<-matrix(rep(0),nrow=m,ncol=n)

#Calculate St
for( j in 1:n){
  St_1<-0
  for(i in 1:m){
    St_1<- max(0,St_1+as.numeric(xt_mu_c[i,j]))
    St[i,j]<-St_1
  }
}

#Set column names
St<-cbind(names(weathermeans),St)

#Plot to check of the threshold is good enough
par(mfcol=c(1,2))

plot(St[,2],type='l')
abline(Thhold,0,col="red")

# Calculate the tipping year

for(i in 1:dim(St)[1]){
  if(St[i,2] > Thhold){
      print("Year when the temperature tipped")
    print(St[i,1])
        break
  }
}
## [1] "Year when the temperature tipped"
## [1] "X2011"
#Average temperature before and after tipping point

print("Before")
## [1] "Before"
mean(weathermeans[1:11])
## [1] 87.50767
print("After")
## [1] "After"
mean(weathermeans[12:20])
## [1] 88.51371

Based on the above averages and the cusum verification we can conclude Atlanta summers have been getting warmer
